{
  "doc_id": "49385",
  "text": "Unfortunately, investigating further when maternal CMV infection is diagnosed can always pose to be a dilemma, as several weeks can elapse before symptomatic fetal infection occurs and abnormal ultrasound features are revealed, especially neurological abnormalities on imaging, sometimes as late as the third trimester [CITATION_1] . The timing of amniocentesis is crucial and is recommended between 21 and 22 weeks of gestation. CMV replicates slowly and can take 6-9 weeks before it is excreted in the fetal urine in large enough amounts to be detected in the amniotic fluid [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . If an invasive procedure is conducted too early, a false negative result could occur [CITATION_4] .",
